<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 93 / Pay rise of 1.5% imposed at BBC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BBC yesterday imposed a 1.5 per cent pay rise without waiting for the
result of a union ballot on the issue. The ballot on whether to accept or
reject the pay deal will not be completed until August 11.
Ms Margaret Salmon, director of personnel, says in a letter to staff: 'We
believe there is nothing to be achieved in awaiting the results of the
ballot and it is intended to implement the 1.5 per cent increase on August 1
1993.'
The BBC points out that pay settlements outside the public sector are
falling and that the government has ruled that public-sector settlements
should be restricted to a maximum of 1.5 per cent of the pay bill.
In her letter Ms Salmon argues that when the BBC is trying to persuade the
government to retain the licence fee to fund the corporation 'we must be
seen to be responsive to general public policy and voluntarily to adopt the
same disciplines that have been imposed on other public-sector
organisations'.
Mr Tony Lennon, president of Bectu, the main broadcasting union, said the
BBC should have waited until the result of the ballot was known. He expected
the majority of staff would vote to reject the offer.
The ballot does not include industrial action and may be used as a stimulus
for talks on other issues such as job cuts. There are fears of further job
losses next year when new budgets are drawn up.
Meanwhile the BBC says it wants to introduce a single contract for
fixed-term workers. The 15 per cent pay premium paid to short-term workers
will be removed in return for limited pension and redundancy rights.
</TEXT>
