<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 93 / Patten in shade as spotlight moves to Blatch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CLIMBDOWN over the national curriculum has posed more questions about
the political future of Mr John Patten, the education secretary, who is
suffering from a stomach illness.
It has also moved the spotlight on to Baroness Blatch, the education
minister, who took responsibility for reacting to the Dearing review in Mr
Patten's absence.
Mr Patten has had an unenviable job, balancing the government's ideological
commitments against the demands of the teachers whose co-operation is vital.
Labour yesterday demanded his resignation, describing the climbdown as 'a
severe embarrassment'.
But Sir Malcolm Thornton, Conservative chairman of the education select
committee, said he did not think yesterday's developments affected Mr
Patten's career.
Lord Skidelsky, a former government adviser who resigned from the Schools
Examination and Assessment Council in May in protest at the way the Dearing
review was carried out, expressed strong opposition to the decision not to
publish league tables for 14-year-olds, or introduce external marking of
tests, and called for 'better leadership'.
He suggested that the government should have persisted with publishing
externally marked league tables for core subjects. 'Maybe that's not
acceptable to the teachers' unions, but it's something we can defend to the
public,' he said. 'The government has never had a clear idea of what it is
doing and therefore the teachers' unions have got a lot of parental
support.'
Some observers are beginning to see Lady Blatch as a possible successor to
Mr Patten. After being appointed his number two after the 1992 general
election, she was one of a handful of ministers tipped to succeed Mr David
Mellor as heritage secretary last September. Her name again cropped up in
May before Mr John Major's first significant reshuffle resulted in Mr John
Redwood's promotion to the cabinet as Welsh secretary. Most recently, her
name surfaced as a possible successor to Lord Wakeham as leader of the
Lords.
A close confidante of Mr Major, Lady Blatch is a member of the so-called
East Anglian mafia at the heart of government - the small group of senior
party figures who live near the prime minister's Huntingdon constituency and
are on close personal terms with him. Other members are Mr Richard Ryder,
the chief whip, Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, and Mrs Gillian
Shephard, agriculture minister.
But her generally traditionalist views on education have done nothing to
offend the right of the party. For example her decision to allow schools to
select up to 10 per cent of pupils on the basis of their ability in
technology was claimed by leftwing educationalists to be a preparation for a
return to selective secondary schools.
She is credited with shepherding a long and complex education bill through
the Lords. According to one government official, she showed 'amazing
stamina' during proceedings that were at times 'tortuous beyond belief' and
demonstrated ability to master a brief 'diligently and quickly'.
She is a former leader of Cambridgeshire County Council, became a peer in
1987 and was appointed a whip in the Lords in 1990, moving to environment
after nine months, then to national heritage. She became a privy counsellor
in the new year honours.
In a government short of stars, perhaps the main obstacle between her and
the cabinet is the traditional sensitivity at Westminster about appointing a
peer to a high-profile post.
She will stay in charge of the education department for at least another
three weeks. Downing Street said Mr Major was delighted that Mr Patten was
'making good progress' in overcoming his illness and was expected to be back
at his desk in the week starting August 23.
</TEXT>
