<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 93 / Limit on sex bias claims is unlawful
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYERS face the prospect of higher claims for compensation from victims
of sex discrimination after the European Court of Justice in Luxembourg
ruled that Britain's statutory Pounds 11,000 ceiling on tribunal awards was
unlawful.
People who have suffered sex discrimination must be compensated in full for
loss and damage actually suffered even if that means exceeding the ceiling.
The government will now have to legislate to remove the statutory
compensation limit.
The court's decision was made in the second case brought by Miss Helen
Marshall, a retired senior dietician, against her former employers
Southampton and South West Hampshire Area Health Authority, which had
dismissed her in 1980 at the age of 62.
In 1986 she won a ruling from the European Court that she could rely on an
EC directive in her action against her employers for discriminatory early
retirement.
The industrial tribunal awarded her Pounds 18,405 in compensation which
included Pounds 7,710 in interest on her financial loss from the date of her
dismissal to the date of the tribunal's decision. In reaching its decision
the tribunal disregarded the Pounds 6,250 limit on compensation.
The health authority paid the capital sum but refused to pay the interest,
and her case was eventually referred back to the European Court.
Lawyers said yesterday the ruling had dramatic implications for UK
employers. Mr David Pannick QC said: 'It is of very great significance for
securing equality in the workplace.
'Employers will now know that there is no statutory limit on the amount of
compensation. They will be making more certain not to discriminate in the
first place, and they will be much more concerned to settle cases rather
than have them go to tribunals.
'Claimants in industrial tribunal awards will receive significantly higher
awards, if they have suffered loss that is above the statutory limit.'
The ruling was welcomed by the Equal Opportunities Commission, which
supported Miss Marshall's case. Ms Kamlesh Bahl, commission head, said the
decision would not only strengthen the UK's sex discrimination laws but also
act as 'a further reminder to employers that it will be costly to
discriminate on grounds of sex.'
The commission said that the first to benefit from the ruling would be the
2,000 women who have filed complaints to tribunals after being sacked for
being pregnant under Ministry of Defence rules which were abandoned in 1990.
Mr Norman Lamb, the lawyer co-ordinating their cases, said the claims of
some of the women could now be as high as Pounds 100,000 or more.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    LUZ  Luxembourg, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
