<PROFILE>_AN-DHCCXABGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930803
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 93 / Employers welcome the new approach: Dearing report
recommends slimmed-down curriculum with testing restricted to English, maths
and science
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and TIM KING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Ron Dearing yesterday opened the way for a shift in England and Wales to
a Continental style of education concentrating on vocational education from
the age of 14, which was generally welcomed by employers.
In a surprising addition to his report, Sir Ron announced that he will
consult until the end of the year on 'the merits of a modified approach to
the curriculum from 14 to 16 which retains a mandatory core but which
provides a smoother transition to study post-16, through a wide range of
options'. He said: 'In the rest of Europe, 16 is not a particularly
significant stage in schooling, and, post-14, many of our neighbours place
particular value on technical and vocational education.'
In France, Germany and the Netherlands 25 per cent of students post-14 go to
schools specialising in vocational education. The National Institute of
Economic and Social Research said earlier this year the national curriculum
in England and Wales had left less academic children 'disadvantaged and
demotivated'.
Continental employers believed pupils who had spent their time from 14 to 16
working on a narrow academic curriculum plus specialised courses in
systematic disciplines such as woodwork and metalwork were more motivated,
according to the institute.
Sir Ron's move was welcomed by employers, although some were alarmed by the
decision not to make testing of technology compulsory. Mr Ian Toombs, of
West London CBI and the Japanese company NEC, said he regarded the national
curriculum as a useful development but there were more deep-rooted problems
in British education than simply the content of the curriculum. A change of
culture was needed to integrate education, training and the workplace, and
the government ought to offer fiscal incentives for employers to involve
themselves in education.
Mr Brian Lindop, manager of educational affairs at Vauxhall Motors, said the
place of technology in the national curriculum had to be defended.
'If we are to compete in the international marketplace we need to improve
the skills of all of our young people in the technology area,' he said.
</TEXT>
