<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / International Company News: Aetna cautious despite advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AETNA Life &amp; Casualty, one of the largest US composite insurers, turned in
improved results for the second quarter. However, it said earnings remained
unsatisfactory.
For the three months to June 30, it posted net income of Dollars 146.1m, or
Dollars 1.32 a share, compared with a loss of Dollars 45.2m, or 41 cents, a
year earlier.
Operating earnings before extraordinary items were Dollars 150.8m, against a
deficit of Dollars 73.1m a year earlier.
Mr Ronald Compton, chairman, said results from core businesses were on track
with expectations, but that company results continued to reflect
unfavourable conditions in commercial real estate markets.
The Hartford, Connecticut-based company said its commercial property and
casualty insurance services earned Dollars 35m in the quarter, against an
underlying loss of Dollars 25m last year, before a Dollars 26m
reorganisation charge. Catastrophe losses narrowed to Dollars 8m in the
latest quarter, from Dollars 11m.
Aetna's financial services business recorded net income of Dollars 17m in
the quarter, compared with a loss of Dollars 22m before reorganisation
charges of Dollars 4m a year earlier.
The personal property-casualty services turned in net income of Dollars 12m,
against Dollars 6m the previous year, before reorganisation charges of
Dollars 30m.
For the first half, net income rose to Dollars 338.7m, or Dollars 3.07,
against earnings of Dollars 73.5m, or 66 cents, a year earlier. Excluding
extraordinary items and the impact of adjustments, income from continuing
operations rose to Dollars 290.1m from Dollars 81.3m. Revenues eased to
Dollars 8.62bn from Dollars 8.78bn.
</TEXT>
