<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Television is often condemned for its triviality, so we can hardly complain
when Channel 4 begins a week of programmes under the general title 'Bloody
Bosnia'. However, after watching the first few items it is hard to believe
that this will attract a very large or dedicated audience. When sticking to
factual content, as in The Essential Guide (9.00) the material tends to look
like schools programmes jazzed up with graphics borrowed from the yoof
department; and when they branch out into entertainment, as in Artists For
Bosnia (11.00) with Ute Lemper singing songs from World War 2, you wonder
what it has to do with Bosnia.
World In Action uses photographs taken by the late Dan Eldon to tell the
story of the war in Somalia. The programme asks whether it was really US
policy in Somalia and the conduct of UN troops that led to his death (8.30
ITV).
Frank Stubbs Promotes is the best comic drama of its sort since 'Minder'.
This week the inept Stubbs is promoting a young female drama student (9.00
ITV).
</TEXT>
