<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / Unions look beyond Labour for support with campaigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIONS ARE increasingly turning to cross-party political lobbying instead of
depending on the eventual return of a Labour government, judging by the
preliminary agenda for this year's Trades Union Congress to be held in
Brighton next month.
Although the campaign by several large TUC unions to retain their influence
in the Labour party is bound to dominate the congress, few motions even
mention the party.
A motion from the CPSA Civil Service union specifically asks that a campaign
to defend public services should 'seek the support of all parties
represented in parliament'. In another motion the CPSA calls for joint
action with the Confederation of British Industry.
The largest number of motions, 11 in all, protest against the government's
latest labour legislation. There is particular concern about some elements
of the Trade Union Reform and Employment Rights Act 1993, including a late
amendment that has the effect of giving employers the right to deny pay
increases to staff who refuse to sign personal contracts.
Mr John Monks, who will take over as TUC general secretary at the end of the
congress when Mr Norman Willis retires, is expected to back this new
campaigning tone. Mr Monks has already made clear that he wishes to
influence all the main political parties and that he does not want 'too many
eggs in one basket'.
He will also, in a keynote speech, set out what sort of TUC he wishes to
lead. Mr Monks takes over at a difficult time for the TUC, with membership
lower than at any time since 1945.
Mr Gavin Laird, general secretary of the AEEU engineering and electrical
union, yesterday stressed the need to loosen ties with Labour. He noted that
the US anti-union legislation of the Reagan-Bush Republican administrations
is being reversed in spite of the lack of formal links between unions and
the Democrats. The percentage of union members paying their dues by direct
debit has nearly doubled from 4.8 per cent to 8 per cent since 1991, the
Labour Research Department, the independent labour movement organisation,
says. However the 'check-off' of dues by employers still remains the most
popular method with 82 per cent paying this way.
</TEXT>
