<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / City considers permanent security cordon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Corporation of London, the City's local authority, is expected to
publish a set of proposals tomorrow designed to reduce the risk of further
bomb attacks by the IRA.
The most controversial measure being considered is the creation of a
permanent security cordon around the City. This would involve maintaining
the road blocks and checkpoints that it installed temporarily last month.
The corporation believes that the predominant acceptance by the public of
the temporary cordon strengthens the case for making it permanent.
The corporation will also propose a range of surveillance measures to
improve security within the City.
These include an increased number of security cameras, neighbourhood watch
schemes and greater co-ordination of companies' security staff and camera
systems.
The corporation also proposes removing all litter bins and rubbish bags from
the streets. It has already taken away 1,000 litter bins following the
Bishopsgate bomb in April.
Other measures include the introduction of a pager alarm system to alert
people to bomb warnings. This would be offered to City workers at a cost of
about Pounds 150 a year each. In the Bishopsgate bomb, some workers were
unable to hear police loud hailers telling them to evacuate buildings.
City businesses and other interested parties will be consulted in the next
few weeks. The consultation document will be widely distributed and the
corporation will also hold a series of public meetings.
The proposals have been drawn up in consultation with a steering committee
on security set up in early June, composed of the City police, the Bank of
England and various securities houses. The corporation has also held
meetings with representatives of more than 400 City businesses.
The measures come in the wake of the recent City bomb attacks. The latest
estimates of the cost of the Bishopsgate bomb is about Pounds 500m, while
the cost of the St Mary Axe bomb a year earlier was about Pounds 350m,
according to the Association of British Insurers.
The Bishopsgate attack increased the pressure on the Corporation of London
to take visible anti-terrorist measures.
The new proposals are designed to restrict the extent of potential bomb
damage - the corporation acknowledges that it cannot prevent hand-carried
devices being brought into the security area.
It has put aside for the time being suggestions that the City should be made
a pedestrian zone because this would involve a lengthy public inquiry.
However Mr Michael Cassidy, who heads the corporation's policy and resources
committee, said that if existing measures worked well there was 'a very real
justification to move forward to pedestrianisation'.
The corporation has written to Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, asking
him to consider giving the police powers to search vehicles. At present the
police can do so only with the owner's permission.
The Home Office has agreed to bear half of the cost of an extra 57 police to
improve security in the City.
</TEXT>
