<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / ICI in 10,000-job project
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF the largest commercial developments in Britain is being planned by
Imperial Chemical Industries on 1,500 acres at Severnside near Bristol. ICI
believes that eventually there could be employment for more than 10,000
people.
ICI describes the land, next to its Severnside works, as a 'major strategic
holding'. Mr Andrew Sturt, group property manager, said: 'We have a
fantastic opportunity and will provide competition for every major site in
the region.'
The company will not act as the sole developer but is in informal
discussions about partnerships which might take the form of joint ventures
or a consortium. Mr Sturt said: 'We will invest money to enhance the
landholding but there is no prospect of ICI entering into development as a
risk-taker. We are concentrating on our core businesses.'
A manufacturing plant, a distribution park and a research park are among
ICI's proposals for what is expected to be at least a decade of development.
Most of the land is let to tenant farmers but there is a long-standing
planning consent for the whole site.
The University of Bristol has agreed to be part of the research park to
develop closer links with industry. It said: 'Precisely what would be in our
building would be decided by the nature of the companies there - it would be
market-led.'
The land, which ICI has owned for more than 30 years, straddles the M49
approach motorway being built to the second Severn crossing, due to open
early in 1996. Planning permission is already being sought for an
interchange with the M49. The site is also close to the M4, the M5 and the
Avonmouth docks.
Mr Robert Durie, of King Sturge, the property adviser to the scheme, said:
'It is a very exciting opportunity. It is of a very significant size and we
are not going to race at it but plan it carefully.'
</TEXT>
