<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / Newspaper price war spreads to The Times
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TIMES yesterday threatened to extend a newspaper price-cutting war to
the broadsheet end of the market by dropping its price by 15p to 30p from
today in one English county.
The experiment, restricted to the part of Kent outside the M25 London
orbital road, is designed to test the conventional wisdom that price is not
a significant factor in the sales of broadsheet newspapers. The price of the
Saturday edition will also fall, from 50p to 35p.
Mr Peter Stothard, editor of The Times, yesterday said that if the
experiment is successful 'we will either continue it or we will extend it'.
The limited Times price cut is likely to be reviewed in September. It comes
three weeks after The Sun - which, like The Times, is owned by News
International - cut its price nationally by 5p to 20p. The Sun move, which
will be reviewed at the end of the summer, has been a modest success with
sales rising about 7 per cent.
In a very different broadsheet market, Mr Stothard says he has a hunch that
'price may be more important than people conventionally think it is'.
Mr Stothard, who emphasised that he was planning his experiment before The
Sun's price cut, said: 'I think it is important to look occasionally at what
is going on in the market and ask fundamental questions. This is one of
those questions.'
The move comes at a time of circulation decline for all the general
broadsheets. In January The Daily Telegraph sold 1.035m a day, The Guardian
424,028, The Times 370,877 and The Independent 353,198.
By June all had fallen, with The Daily Telegraph on 1.012m although it was
pursuing an aggressive price policy at 48p, The Guardian at 406,627; The
Times 362,428 and The Independent 338,828. The Independent, The Times and
The Guardian all cost 45p.
Mr Stothard, who says his readers write to complain about the price of the
paper, hopes that readers in Kent who do not buy the paper every day will be
encouraged to move to six days a week by the price cut.
Mr Andreas Whittam Smith, editor of The Independent, whose paper could be
most seriously affected by any national cut in The Times's price, declined
to comment last night other than to say: 'We will have to think about it.'
</TEXT>
