<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / Strategy on jobs 'beats EC rivals'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK government is 'winning the argument' with its European partners about
how to combat unemployment by reducing employment regulation and increasing
labour flexibility, according to Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary.
He was speaking yesterday as the Treasury and his own department released
separate submissions to European Commission reviews of competition and
employment.
The Treasury submission says that improving skills and productivity is not,
as often argued, in conflict with reducing the high cost and strict
regulation of labour. 'On the contrary, if the costs of employment are too
high, profits are reduced and investment in both capital goods and human
skills is held back,' the report states.
'For many unemployed people the chance to return to work is more important
than the nature of the work or its terms and conditions. Temporary or
part-time jobs can be a route back into work, enabling people to move into
more traditional full-time jobs later if they wish,' it continues.
It says that EC labour costs rose by 4 per cent per year during the 1980s
compared with 0 to 1 per cent in the US and Japan. Also, public social
security and healthcare as a proportion of GDP is nearly twice as high in
the EC compared with Japan and more than 60 per cent higher than in the US.
The Treasury strongly rejects the idea that there should be a provision in
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade to control the imports of goods
from economies with low labour costs. It recommends instead that the EC
should do more to remove the barriers to enterprise and monitor more
carefully the effects on jobs and competition of all new regulations.
The employment department submission to the Social Affairs Directorate
General's green paper review of employment legislation, due in the autumn,
said that co-operation between member states was usually preferable to
legislation.
Where legislation is necessary it should only be drawn up after much wider
consultation than is customary and should just set a general framework
allowing individual countries to fill in details.
</TEXT>
