   By DAVID GOODHART and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is 'winning the argument' with its European partners about
how to combat unemployment by reducing employment regulation and increasing
labour flexibility, according to Mr David Hunt, employment secretary.
He was speaking yesterday as the Treasury and his own department released
separate submissions to European Commission reviews of competition and
employment.
The Treasury submission says that improving skills and productivity is not,
as often argued, in conflict with reducing the high cost and strict
regulation of labour. It adds: 'On the contrary, if the costs of employment
are too high, profits are reduced and investment in both capital goods and
human skills is held back.'
The report says that EC labour costs rose by 4 per cent a year during the
1980s compared with 0 per cent to 1 per cent in the US and Japan. Also,
