FT  02 AUG 93 / Blow for Lloyd's as finance chief quits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYD'S OF LONDON, the troubled insurance market, has suffered a fresh blow
with the surprise resignation of Mr David Bruce, its finance director, after
only four months.
News of his departure after only four months in the job emerged yesterday.
Last night Lloyd's offered no explanation but said that Mr Stephen Hall, a
former partner with Ernst &amp; Young, the accountancy firm, had been appointed
to the vacancy.
Mr Bruce, who is in his mid-40s, was formerly group finance director at
Guinness Mahon, the merchant bank. Before that he was director of finance
and administration at the Stock Exchange.
He was appointed to the post at Lloyd's in March in succession to Mr John
Gaynor. He is one of a new breed of more commercially minded executives
introduced to the Corporation of Lloyd's, which administers and regulates
the Lloyd's market, by Mr Peter Middleton, the chief executive, and Mr David
Rowland, the chairman.
Mr Bruce's initial reponsibilities included supervising the attraction of
corporate investors to the market, although within the past six weeks
Lloyd's has appointed another outsider, Mr Ewen Gilmour, to manage this
process under Mr Bruce.
Mr Hall, 60, retired early from Ernst &amp; Young, where he took a close
interest in eastern European privatisations.
