<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / Banks trail French on costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH BANKS are the second most efficient in western Europe after the
French in terms of their ratio of costs to income, an analysis of human
resources in banking says. This is because the cost of employing staff
outside Britain is on average 2 1/2 times higher.
The study by the financial services analysis company Lafferty Group finds
that ratio of cost to income per employee in 1990 was 25.3 per cent in
Britain against 22.2 per cent in France. The highest ratio was 41.7 per cent
in Switzer-land and 40.1 per cent in Italy.
The figures are based on data from 400 of the 500 largest banks in 25
European countries. They provide a benchmark for the year when most European
banks were about to embark on cost-reduction programmes to improve staff
efficiency after widespread expansion in the late 1980s.
However, they also disclose wide differentials in the ratios of income,
assets and profits to employees in different countries. Many banks have had
trouble controlling overseas operations and several British banks are this
week expected to report high bad debts on French subsidiaries.
The Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building Society achieved one of the lowest
ratio of costs to income per employee in Europe at 14 per cent, being beaten
only by Ippa Bank in Belgium with 11 per cent. The National Bank of Greece
had the highest reported ratio at 70 per cent.
German banks were the most efficient in terms of the size of balance sheets
compared with number of employees. The average German bank held Ecu10.3m
(Pounds 7.77m) in loans per employee, compared with Ecu6.24m in Switzerland
and Ecu2.84m in Britain.
British banks and building societies had the highest proportion of part-time
employees, with Newcastle Building Society having 36.8 per cent part-time
workers compared with an average of 10 per cent among European bank
employees. All but 2 per cent of UK part-timers were women.
Human Resources in European Banking. Lafferty Publications, The Tower, IDA
Centre, Pearse Street, Dublin 2, Ireland. Pounds 399.
</TEXT>
