<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / Cross-party unity on unemployment urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR David Hunt, employment secretary, has called for a national consensus
between the main political parties on a strategy for tackling long-term
unemployment.
Mr Hunt, a standard-bearer of the left in the Tory party, said at the
weekend: 'It has now become such an intractable problem that we must find a
way of involving people from across the whole political spectrum. If you can
get a general agreement, it allows you to move away from stale arguments
about resources.'
About a third of the 2.9m unemployed have been out of work for more than a
year, and the proportion is likely to rise even if unemployment as a whole
continues to fall.
Mr Hunt said he had received indications from many people 'across the
political and industrial spectrum' that they would be ready to work with the
government. He would not name individuals, but he has a close rapport with
both Mr Frank Field, the Labour MP who is chairman of the Commons' social
security committee, and Mr John Monks, general secretary-elect of the Trades
Union Congress.
Mr Hunt has just returned from a short tour of the US, where he was
promoting inward investment in the UK and looking at workfare schemes, which
require the unemployed to work for their benefit.
He said he had 'reservations' about the element of compulsion in such
schemes and pointed out that the US has a very different, and generally less
generous, benefit system. But he also noted that it was the Democrats, and
not the Republicans, who were now considering introducing a national
workfare scheme. 'I think President Clinton's friends in the Labour party
should take note of that,' he said.
Mr Hunt also reached agreement on funding a joint study of how the US
economy has produced so many new jobs over the past few years. 'Europe has a
lot to learn from the US experience, but it seems that there is no clear
idea in the US as to why they have been so successful,' he said.
The Labour Party does not share Mr Hunt's enthusiasm for the highly
deregulated US labour market, where more than two-thirds of all employees
can be fired at will. Mr Frank Dobson, Labour's employment spokesman,
yesterday said that low employment protection and low wages in Britain had
not solved the unemployment problem.
</TEXT>
