FT  02 AUG 93 / Midlands councils appeal for EC funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL authorities in the west Midlands are appealing for European Community
regional funding to help regenerate the economy.
The authorities hope both the UK government and the EC will adopt their
strategy in their definition of regional spending policy over the next five
years.
In their document the authorities say EC funding 'has been a mainstay of
urban regeneration policy in the West Midlands'.
But they acknowledge that previous EC funding - more than Pounds 300m since
1988 - failed to make 'any real inroads into combating . . . inner-city
poverty' or to counteract recession. Spending was also often poorly
integrated with local development priorities.
The focus of new spending should be on arresting the decline of
manufacturing, improving communications, helping small and medium-sized
businesses, developing tourism and enhancing research and development
capacity.
The government's new map of areas eligible for regional assistance raise
Birmingham from intermediate to development status, widening the scope of
funding for which companies can apply.
The West Midlands Region, European Development Strategy. West Midlands
Regional Forum of Local Authorities, PO Box 11, Martin Street, Stafford ST16
2LH. Pounds 20.
