<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / Insurer launches NHS trust scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NEW medical insurance plan that provides treatment in National Health
Service trust hospitals rather than the private sector is to be launched
today.
Norwich Union Healthcare estimates that insurance under its Trust Care
scheme will be 25 per cent to 30 per cent cheaper than its full-cover
policies. Trust Care offers many of the regular benefits of health insurance
policies but excludes the use of private hospitals. Patients will instead
receive treatment in private wings of NHS trusts.
The development is likely to alarm the private hospital sector, which is
already concerned that since the 1991 NHS reforms some trust managers have
started encouraging consultants to carry out private practice on NHS
premises rather than in independent hospitals.
Norwich Union's marketing material for the new plan describes it as an
affordable medical insurance policy that has been developed 'in conjunction
with NHS hospitals'.
Mr David Cavers, managing director of Norwich Union Healthcare, said the
scheme would bring 'high-quality medical cover within the reach of
individuals and families who may not have previously considered it', while
generating income for the NHS.
Norwich Union has compiled a list of 'preferred' trust hospitals that have
agreed to provide treatment - normally with single room accommodation - and
settle bills direct with the insurer.
The list contains many of the NHS's best-known hospitals including Guy's-St
Thomas', University College-Middlesex, St Mary's, Royal Brompton, King's
College, Charing Cross, the Royal London and the Great Ormond Street
Hospital for Sick Children in London; Papworth in Cambridge; Leeds General
Infirmary; and the Queen Elizabeth, Birmingham.
Private wings and pay beds have always been a feature of the NHS and since
the introduction of market-based reforms hospital managers have been trying
to increase income by revamping these facilities. But low bed occupancy is a
feature shared by some NHS private wings and independent hospitals. Norwich
Union estimates that bed occupancy in NHS private facilities nationally
averages about 30 per cent.
Mr Ian Robertson, business manager of the Lindo private wing at St Mary's,
Paddington, said that involvement in Trust Care would help to ensure that
the hospital's private facilities were used efficiently while not affecting
the provision of public beds. The scheme would be 'providing care and
comfort comparable with the private sector while channelling funds back into
the hospital'.
The new scheme from Norwich Union, one of the most forceful recent entrants
to the health insurance market, would cost Pounds 19.64 per month for a
27-year-old in Oxford, Pounds 30.65 for a 29-year-old in inner London and
Pounds 64.92 for a typical family.
An NOP Omnibus survey for Norwich Union showed that eight out of 10 people
believed the NHS should be able to generate income from its private
facilities.
</TEXT>
