<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / Pay slides at small firms of architects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE heads of small architecture practices are suffering more in the building
industry recession than their colleagues in larger firms, earnings figures
today from the Royal Institute of British Architects show, Andrew Baxter
writes.
Earnings of sole principals - the heads of small practices - fell 16 per
cent in the year ended April 1 to a median level of Pounds 15,072. It is the
third consecutive year that sole principals' income has fallen and the
cumulative fall in earnings has been 37 per cent since 1990.
Principals in partnership, working for larger firms, saw median earnings
fall 9 per cent to Pounds 25,489 in 1992-93. Overall, the average earnings
of full-time architects on April 1 was Pounds 23,175 - a 1 per cent rise on
last year's figure but still lower than the 1991 average.
Private-sector in-house architects and those in local government fared
better, with rises in income of 3 per cent and 4 per cent respectively.
</TEXT>
