<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / Israel blocks deportation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Israel's Supreme Court, after clearing Mr John Demjanjuk last week of being
Nazi death camp guard 'Ivan the Terrible', blocked his deportation to
Ukraine yesterday while considering if he can stand trial for other war
crimes, Reuter reports from Jerusalem.
A five-judge court acquitted Mr Demjanjuk.
Yesterday a separate three-judge panel, acting on a complaint by two
Israelis, gave government prosecutors seven days to show why Mr Demjanjuk
should not be investigated anew based on allegations that he was a guard at
other Nazi camps.
'The discussion will resume in 10 days. In seven days the attorney-general
will submit his arguments, and he won't be deported until then,' presiding
judge Mr Shlomo Levin said.
A former car worker, Mr Demjanjuk was stripped of his US citizenship in 1981
for concealing his wartime activities when he entered America and moved to
Cleveland, Ohio, after the second world war.
He was extradited to Israel in 1986 and still hopes to regain his US
citizenship over objections by the Justice Department.
</TEXT>
