<TEXT>
MR Kenneth Clarke, Britain's chancellor of the exchequer, was seeking
yesterday to play the honest broker between the warring factions in
continental Europe as finance ministers met, writes Peter Marsh in Brussels.
There were suggestions in the Belgian capital that he would use the UK
experience to offer a constructive way out of the exchange rate mechanism
impasse, perhaps by suggesting that other countries follow Britain's lead
and allow currencies to float outside the system, so allowing lower interest
