<PROFILE>_AN-DHBCDAAQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930802
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / The ERM Crisis: Flexibility is key to ERM restyling - Looser
system evolves for linking Europe's currencies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European exchange rate mechanism lives to fight another day - but only
just.
This morning's agreement by European Community finance ministers in Brussels
 -reached only minutes before the markets opened in Tokyo - provides a
revamped, new-look ERM which is completely different from the system's
architecture when it was sketched out in 1979.
The accord, hammered out after nearly 12 hours of negotiations, provides for
a minimalist form of currency linkage involving fluctuation bands of 15 per
cent - much bigger than the 2.25 per cent bands which until today applied
for most of the system's eight currencies.
The ministers' preferred solution to patching up the mechanism was forced on
them after unprecedented selling of weak ERM currencies at the end of last
week which brought the mechanism close to collapse. The talks exposed deep
divisions among the EC member states about the kind of framework for
currency co-operation which they wanted.
It featured strong determination by Germany in particular to see constructed
a more flexible ERM which would reduce the heavy intervention operations
which the Bundesbank has been forced into during the past year as part of
the effort of propping up weak ERM currencies.
While Britain appeared to play a constructive role in using its own
experiences of being ousted from the ERM last year as providing useful
lessons for the system's future operation, the meeting exposed Spain as the
one EC nation firmly in the camp of suspending the system's rules at least
temporarily to allow currencies to float and so permit lower interest rates.
What emerges from today's agreement is a much looser system for keeping
currencies close to each other. It will be seen by some hardline ERM
supporters as a dilution of the idea of forcing different countries'
economies to converge by enforcing only restricted movement by their
respective currencies around a central rate.
On these grounds, some will doubt whether the overall goals of the ERM have
been retained.
However, the revamp answers the strong conjecture that because of the
inflationary implications of German unification the role of the D-Mark as
the ERM anchor had been seriously weakened. By permitting a much greater
degree of currency movement, the new operating rules should provide extra
flexibility that could deter further reduction in investor confidence.
A further plus, in the eyes of the designers of the new-look ERM, is that in
theory it should be able to provide for lower interest rates by several of
the countries in the system. And by retaining the existing central parities
against then D-Mark of all the seven other currencies in the mechanism, it
ensures that no country will have to admit to having agreed to a politically
humiliating devaluation.
Mr Theo Waigel, German finance minister, told reporters that Germany had
produced the first proposals for resolving the ERM crisis. These focused on
two areas: widening the fluctuation bands and suspending the obligations to
intervene on behalf of weaker member currencies.
Underlying the German move was a desire to preserve the European monetary
system and the ERM parity grid. This was the minimum area of agreement
reached during Saturday's discussions of the EC's monetary committee.
Mr Waigel said there had been 'many, many rounds of talks' between member
states, often chaired by Belgium which holds rotating presidency of the
European Community. The proposal to suspend the ERM's operating rules was
strongly resisted by the European Commission.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BEZ  Belgium, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT933-10894</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DHBCDAAPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930802
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / The ERM Crisis: Ministers back current parities - Communique
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
EC finance ministers and central bank governors issued the following
statement after their meeting in Brussels:
'THE ministers and central bank governors of the member states of the EC
have decided to widen temporarily the obligatory marginal intervention
thresholds of the participants in the ERM to plus or minus 15 per cent
around the bilateral central rates.
This measure of limited duration is in response to speculative movements
which are exceptional in amount as well as in nature.
Indeed, having regard to the fundamental economic situation of the member
states participating in the system, the current parity grid is fully
justified. The ministers and governors therefore reaffirm support for the
current parities and are confident that the market rates will soon approach
these parities once again.
The monetary authorities of the member states will continue to direct their
monetary policy towards the aim of price stability.
All the member states reaffirm their determination to put the treaty on
European union into operation as soon as its ratification is complete,
including the evaluation procedure which according to article 109E must take
place before January 1 1994, the start of stage two. Moreover, they reaffirm
their support for the procedures and criteria laid down in the treaty with
respect to the attainment of a sufficient degree of convergence in order to
allow the realisation of economic and monetary union.
The new compulsory intervention rates will be communicated by the monetary
authorities in time for the opening of foreign exchange markets on August
2.'
</TEXT>
