<DOCNO>FT933-10898</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DHBCDAALFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930802
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / The ERM Crisis: Seguin poised to be political winner
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN and JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IF THERE is one Frenchman who might stand to gain politically from a change
in the franc fort policy it is Mr Philippe Seguin, the National Assembly
president who has made no secret of his desire to see France unhook its
currency from the D-Mark and reflate its economy with lower interest rates.
If such a change is forced on France in the near future it could make Mr
Seguin a contender for the presidency in 1995, according to Mr Dominique
Mosi, deputy director of France's Institute for International Relations.
'Seguin has put his entire weight behind France devaluing the franc and
following a British-style economic policy,' he says.
The leading Gaullist opponent of the Maastricht treaty in last September's
referendum campaign, Mr Seguin got his present job, in which he presides
over parliament but does not lead its conservative majority, because the
Balladur government wanted to park him in a largely honorary post. But
outside parliament Mr Seguin has refused to let his views be sidelined.
He has hammered away at the need for government to worry less about its
budget deficit and more about unemployment, while attacking Gatt and calling
for more trade protection. He has recently soft-pedalled his views on
European monetary matters, but these have not changed markedly since his
call last December for France to 'cut the franc's link with the D-Mark - and
quick'.
When Gaullist ministers called last week for 'unity behind the franc,' their
clear target was Mr Seguin. But it is significant that Mr Jacques Chirac,
the Gaullists' leader and still the party's most likely presidential
contender, has been laconic in his comments on the franc, aware that
monetary events may be moving in Mr Seguin's favour.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>PEOP  People.
</TP>
