<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / EC mounts ERM rescue bid: Fluctuation of 15% for currencies
as ministers seek to resolve crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN Community finance ministers reached an historic agreement early
today to revamp radically the operating rules of the embattled exchange rate
mechanism in a bid to salvage it.
After more than 11 hours of emergency talks in Brussels, the finance
ministers and central bank governors from the 12 member states agreed to
widen the fluctuation bands for the eight currencies in the ERM to 15 per
cent.
This represents a last-ditch bid to make the ERM more flexible and allow
broader leeway for movement of currencies to make the system less
susceptible to speculative attack.
The new 15 per cent bands will come into place from the start of trading in
Europe today. They replace the 2.25 per cent margins now applying for all
currencies in the system apart from the Spanish peseta and Portuguese
escudo, which up until this morning had 6 per cent fluctuation bands.
But this makes the ERM a 'minimalist' system which may be seen as
ineffective in keeping currencies tied together.
French economy minister Edmond Alphandery said that franc stability, both
domestically and on foreign exchange markets, would remain the overriding
priority of French monetary policy. 'Let there be no mistake. The direction
of monetary policy remains unchanged,' he said.
Mr Theo Waigel, German finance minister, said that widening the fluctuation
bands - and so reducing the need for German and Dutch intervention - was
just a temporary measure to relieve tensions inside the ERM.
The aim was to return to narrow bands by January 1 next year, when the
second stage of European economic and monetary union is due to begin under
the Maastricht treaty.
Mr Helmut Schlesinger, Bundesbank president, expressed satisfaction with the
widening of the bands, saying it would increase risks for speculators and
would hopefully mean a relaxation in tensions. He made clear that the
Bundesbank had not made an explicit commitment to lower interest rates as
part of this morning's agreement.
Mr Schlesinger said that Germany had fulfilled more than its duties in
supporting the weaker currencies. But the Bundesbank had recently spent more
than DM60bn (Pounds 23bn) buying weaker currencies in voluntary and
obligatory intervention.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the UK chancellor, said after the meeting the solution
was 'flexible and realistic'. He reaffirmed that Britain would be unlikely
for some time to want to return to the ERM.
In a communique, the finance ministers said all member states reaffirmed
their determinatiom to put the Maastricht treaty on European monetary union
into operation as soon as possible.
The weekend talks came after hectic selling of weak currencies in the ERM at
the end of last week. Especially badly hit by the selling were the Belgian
and French francs and the Danish krone, leaving only the D-Mark, the Irish
punt and the Dutch guilder unscathed.
The currency crisis was triggered by the Bundesbank's refusal to lower its
key discount rate on Thursday.
The new 15 per cent bands will be based around the existing central rates of
currencies in the ERM against each other and against the anchor currency,
the D-Mark.
Crucially, the Netherlands and Germany will retain their existing
relationship allowing for only a 2.25 per cent fluctuation margin between
the D-Mark and the Dutch guilder. This reinforces the impression of a
multi-tier currency grid, according to officials.
Mr Waigel said that one country - known to be Spain - had called for
suspension of the operating rules of the ERM but this suggestion had met
with strong opposition from the European Commission, on the grounds that it
could be misunderstood by financial markets.
Mr Henning Christophersen, vice-president of the European Commission, said
the deal was a temporary response 'to exceptional circumstances created by
market speculation'.
He stressed the need for close co-operation between governments and central
banks to avoid unnecessary fluctuations.
Under the deal intervention rules will apply as under the normal system
except that they will occur only at the top and lower end of the fluctuation
rate of 15 per cent.
Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, said: 'The deal was the best
that could be achieved.' But he added that it was not wholly satisfactory,
apparently referring to suggestions that wider fluctuation bands would
reduce the effectiveness of the ERM in keeping currencies together.
Mr Clarke said the changes in the ERM rules would leave member states free
to pursue their own policies. The changes 'keep the system intact but make
it a much more flexible arrangement'. Although sterling fell with the new
wide bands there was no question of an early sterling re-entry to the ERM.
Britain pulled sterling from the mechanism last autumn, saying it would not
rejoin until ''fault lines'' in the system had been fixed.
In their communique, the EC ministers and central bankers reaffirmed their
support for procedures laid down in the Maastricht treaty for achieving
economic convergence in the Community. They said the new wider bands of the
EC's currency grid were a temporary response to exceptional speculative
movements.
'The ministers and governors therefore reaffirm support for the current
parities and are confident that the market rates will soon approach these
parities once again.'
Mr Wim Kok, Dutch finance minister, said Spain was the only country strongly
in favour of a general float of the currencies in the ERM.
'Spain alone argued vigorously for a general float,' he said after the
meeting. He said that no country asked for a general realignment.
Asked what he thought of the decision to widen fluctuation bands to 15 per
cent. Mr Kok said: 'This was the worst but one option.'
He believed a smaller widening of the bands with variations between
different countries, or the D-Mark and guilder temporarily leaving the
system would have been preferable.
'This is an almost floating system with the exception of Germany and the
Netherlands,' Mr Kok said.
'A collapse would have been a disaster. This is not a disaster but it is a
black day.'
Mr Norman Lamont, Britain's former chancellor, said the decision to loosen
ties between currencies in the ERM had killed all plans for a single EC
currency.
'It's clear monetary union is now dead and the monetary part of the
Maastricht treaty has been made redundant,' he said.
The French franc's crisis was the same as the pound's last year.
'Like the UK, France does not have high inflation and no amount of political
commitment was sufficient to cope with German monetary conditions when they
became wholly inappropriate for the rest of Europe,' Mr Lamont said,
referring to interest rates.
In Paris, a spokesman for Mr Edouard Balladur, the French prime minister,
said he would be making no statement on the talks until today.
Officials had said earlier that he could make a statement after the talks in
Brussels ended.
THE ERM CRISIS
