<HEADLINE>
FT  02 AUG 93 / Move amounts to suspension of system say dealers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WIDENING of the bands in the exchange rate mechanism in effect amounts
to a free float of European Community currencies, foreign exchange dealers
in London believe.
Early today some predicted further selling of the French franc, which
weakened sharply in Far Eastern markets immediately after the decision in
Brussels.
Several analysts said that the move by Community finance ministers,
announced in the early hours of this morning, was extraordinary because it
allowed EC currencies to fluctuate against the D-Mark by such a large
amount.
However, some dealers suggested that the decision could bring a resolution
of the key issue in the currency crisis, which is that France must be able
to cut its interest rates to boost the economy.
There was no announcement by the French authorities after the meeting, but
some analysts expected France to ease monetary policy this week, possibly
today.
'It would have been useful if Germany had cut rates,' said Mr Julian
Simmonds head of foreign exchange at Citibank in London. 'But given the 15
per cent bands, countries have now got the room to cut their rates and allow
their currencies to get weaker.'
Other market participants were more critical of the move. Mr Jeremy Hawkins,
chief economic adviser at Bank of America, said that it would have been far
better to announce the suspension of the ERM. 'It makes a mockery of the
system,' he said. 'It effectively means that you have a 30 per cent trading
range for the French franc against the D-Mark, and that is clearly absurd.'
He did not rule out the possibility that the French franc would come under
more selling pressure in European trading today.
Mr Paul Chertkow, global currency strategist at Union Bank of Switzerland in
London, said that the weekend-long meeting showed that Germany was unwilling
to save the ERM.
'This is obviously a clear message from the Germans that they are not
prepared to do anything for the system,' he said.
The news came amid growing tension in currency markets, with several London
dealing rooms well staffed with dealers trading the French franc.
In an unusual out-of-hours trading session in London and New York late last
night, dealers pushed the French franc well below its previous floor in the
exchange rate mechanism before the announcement from Brussels, in the belief
that Europe's monetary system was in mortal danger. The Spanish peseta was
also bought below its floor.
After the announcement from Brussels came through, the D-Mark appreciated
against most currencies, pushing the French franc down to about FFr3.4762 in
early Far Eastern trading, some 4 1/2 centimes below its former ERM floor.
The D-Mark also appreciated strongly against the dollar, as dealers in the
Far East sold weaker European currencies in the belief that there was room
for them to depreciate.
In Tokyo, the dollar fell back to around DM1.7355, having been close to the
DM1.75 level at one stage. Sterling fell back to DM2.575 from a previous
London close of DM2.585.
</TEXT>
