FT  31 JUL 93 / How to Spend It: Could amber be the choice for you?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCIA VAN DER POST
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF YOU prefer your jewellery chunky, bold and ethnic amber may well be the
choice for you. Back in May I reported that amber was the stone of the
summer with Cobra &amp; Bellamy kicking the amber season off with a spectacular
selection of rich, raw and brutal pieces culled from the ancient fossilised
forests around the Baltic Sea.
Since then the choices have proliferated and you can buy amber jewellery in
many moods and at many prices. You can buy a small selection by mail order
from Muftec Consultancy, 27 Coval Road, London SW14 7RW. There are amber
rings (Pounds 28) and a good selection of ear-rings (ranging from Pounds 35
to Pounds 65) as well as bracelets (Pounds 85), brooches (Pounds 45 to
Pounds 65) and an amber and fancy silver collar (Pounds 95). All the pieces
uses silver for the setting and all are made from amber found on the Baltic
coast of Poland or Lithuania, each piece is hand-cut and hand-made. Write to
Muftec for a brochure.
Next and most branches of John Lewis are selling well-priced pieces from the
Goldmajor collection of amber jewellery - ear-rings start at Pounds 16.45
and for around Pounds 30 there is plenty of choice. At the top end of the
range the mosaic necklaces are quite spectacular.
At Manguette, 20a Kensington Church Walk, London W8, a small but charming
jewellery shop, there will be an exhibition of contemporary amber jewellery,
September 15-29, with contemporary designers such as John Bowman, Gatto
Bianco, Ashley Wheeler and Eileen Coyne. Prices range from Pounds 50 to
Pounds 2,500.
If you want something to wear with your summer wardrobe you do not have to
wait until September - Manguette always has a marvellous selection of amber
pieces. Available now is the stunning necklace, above, designed by Eileen
Coyne, made from Baltic amber, and selling for Pounds 795.
