<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Heavy profit-taking by
blue-chips lowers Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
HEAVY profit-taking in blue-chip stocks meant US equity markets ended most
lower across the board yesterday, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 27.95 at 3,539.47.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended down 2.11 at 448.13,
while the Amex composite finished 0.41 firmer at 437.00, and the Nasdaq
composite down 2.52 at 704.70. Trading volume on the NYSE was 250m shares.
The markets ended a difficult week on a downbeat note. On Thursday stocks
had posted gains in spite of disappointing news on second quarter economic
growth, primarily because the weak gross GDP led to a sharp drop in bond
yields, which is always good news for equity investors.
Yesterday, however, the markets were unable to sustain their upward momentum
as profit-taking swept the blue-chip sector. Prices opened weaker, but it
was not until bond prices turned notably lower at mid-morning that the
selling in the stock markets gathered pace. The reversal in bond prices,
which pushed the yield on the benchmark 30-year bond back up to 6.6 per
cent, was only temporary, and by late afternoon the 30-year yield was back
nearer 6.5 per cent. Among individual stocks, Minnesota Mining &amp;
Manufacturing tumbled Dollars 3 1/2 to Dollars 105 after the big industrial
group announced a modest increase in second quarter earnings to Dollars
331m. The stock declined in spite of a warning from the company earlier this
year about their profits outlook.
The big insurance group Aetna also fell on earnings news, the stock slipping
Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 58 3/8 . Walt Disney remained troubled by its
recently disappointing profits report, falling another Dollars 1 1/8 to
Dollars 37 1/2 in volume of 2.5m shares.
Profit-taking took its toll on a variety of leading Dow stocks, including
Allied Signal, down Dollars 1 1/4 at Dollars 70 1/8 , Eastman Kodak, down
Dollars  1/8 at Dollars 53 3/4 , Coca-Cola, down Dollars 3/4 at Dollars 43
1/4 , and Caterpillar, lower Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 76 7/8 .
Improved earnings continued to help car stocks, with General Motors climbing
Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 48 1/2 .
AL Laboratories slumped Dollars 9 to Dollars 14 5/8 in busy trading after
the company warned that it would struggle to equal to match last year's
operating earnings result. On the Nasdaq market, the big story was
Microsoft, which tumbled Dollars 5 to Dollars 74 in volume of 9m shares as
investors reacted negatively to Thursday's late warning from the company
about future revenue growth and software prices, which will be kept low by
competitive pressures. Several leading Wall Street brokerage houses cut
their earnings forecasts after the warning.
Canada
TORONTO closed higher in active trading, helped by a 1.48 per cent rise in
the gold index as bullion prices soared.
The TSE composite index gained 9.68 to close at 3,967.23.
</TEXT>
<XX>
